summary:
Here is a clear and concise summary of the Security Council document:

The Security Council,

Noting with concern the tense situation in the Middle East, 
Having considered reports on the United Nations Disengagement Observer Force (UNDOF),
Stressing the need for parties to abide by the 1974 Disengagement of Forces Agreement and observe the ceasefire,

Condemns ongoing military activities that escalate tensions between Israel and the Syrian Arab Republic, 
Appreciates UNDOF's liaison efforts to prevent escalation,

Expresses concern at violence in the Syrian Arab Republic and violations of the Disengagement of Forces Agreement,
Calls for parties to cease military actions and respect international humanitarian law,

Notes the threat to UN personnel from unexploded ordnance and emphasizes the need for demining operations,
Reaffirms readiness to list individuals and entities supporting ISIL or Al-Nusra Front,

Recognizes the need for UNDOF to adjust its posture to minimize security risks,
Emphasizes the importance of access to reports and information related to UNDOF's redeployment configuration,

Underscores the need for UNDOF to have necessary means and resources to carry out its mandate safely,
Expresses appreciation to UNDOF personnel for their service,

Strongly condemns incidents threatening the safety and security of United Nations personnel,
Welcomes steps to enhance UNDOF's safety and security,

Takes note of the Secretary-General's plan for UNDOF to return to the Bravo side,
Recalls that UNDOF's deployment and the 1974 Disengagement of Forces Agreement are steps toward a just and durable peace.
Recalling resolution 2242 (2015) and its aspiration to increase the number of women in military and police contingents of United Nations peacekeeping operations,

1. Calls upon parties to implement resolution 338 (1973) immediately;

2. Stresses both parties' obligation to fully respect the 1974 Disengagement of Forces Agreement, exercise maximum restraint, prevent ceasefire breaches, and utilize UNDOF's liaison function;

3. Underlines UNDOF's impartiality and stresses the importance of halting activities that endanger peacekeepers and ensuring their freedom to carry out their mandate;

4. Expresses support for the Secretary-General's appointment of Major General Ishwar Hamal as Head of Mission and Force Commander;

5. Calls on all groups to abandon UNDOF positions and return peacekeepers' vehicles, weapons, and equipment;

6. Calls on parties to cooperate with UNDOF operations, respect its privileges and immunities, and ensure its freedom of movement and security;

7. Calls on parties to support UNDOF's use of the Quneitra crossing and lift COVID-19 related restrictions;

8. Requests UNDOF to protect personnel safety, security, and health, considering the COVID-19 pandemic;

9. Welcomes UNDOF's efforts to consolidate its presence and intensify operations in the area of separation;

10. Underscores the importance of progress in deploying appropriate technology to ensure UNDOF personnel's safety and security;

11. Encourages parties to engage constructively to facilitate UNDOF's return to the area of separation;

12. Encourages discussions on recommendations to improve UNDOF's performance and mandate implementation;

13. Welcomes initiatives to standardize a culture of performance in UN peacekeeping and reaffirms support for a comprehensive performance policy framework;

14. Requests the Secretary-General to ensure compliance with the UN's zero-tolerance policy on sexual exploitation and abuse;

15. Decides to renew UNDOF's mandate until 31 December 2020 and requests the Secretary-General to ensure UNDOF has required capacity and resources;

16. Requests the Secretary-General to report every 90 days on developments and measures taken to implement resolution 338 (1973).
